history|South Asia]]\n[[Category:Genetics by country|South Asia]]\n[[Category:South Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Peipsi-Pihkva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eY Chromosome variation:East Europeans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetics_and_archaeogenetics_of_South_Asia"}
{"title_page": "Werner Krolikowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|honorific-prefix    = \n|birth_name    = \n|name = Werner Krolikowski\n|image = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1983-0506-026, Werner Krolikowski.jpg\n|caption = Werner Krolikowski (1985)\n|imagesize     = \n|order = \n|term_start = \n|term_end = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1928|3|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Ole\u015bnica|Oels]], [[Province of Lower Silesia]], [[Weimar Germany|Germany]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|occupation   = Politician\n|party   =   [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]]\n|spouse        =  \n|parents =    \n|children =  \n}}\n'''Werner Krolikowski''' (born 12 March 1928 <ref>[https://www.chronikderwende.de/lexikon/biografien/biographie_jsp/key=krolikowski_werner.html Chronik der Wende: Werner Krolikowski]</ref>) is an [[East Germany|East German]] political official who became a senior politician. He was a member of the Central Committee of the ruling [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED (party)]] politburo and a deputy chairman of the national [[Council of Ministers of the GDR|Council of Ministers]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1918|author1=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]|author2=[[:de:Andreas Herbst (Historiker)|Andreas Herbst]]|title=Krolikowski, Werner * 12.3.1928 Mitglied des Politb\u00fcros des ZK der SED, 1. Stellv. des Vorsitzenden des Ministerrats|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref> He also produced a number of political publications.\n\n==Life==\n===Early years===\nWerner Krolikowski was born into a working-class family.   He trained for office work.   By the time the [[Second world war|war]] ended the frontier between Poland and Germany had [[Oder-Neisse line|moved west]] and Krolikowski, along with millions of other Germans, [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|had also moved]], the town of his birth now being part of Poland.  In 1946 he joined the newly formed [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED / ''Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands'')]] in the [[Soviet occupation zone]] of what was left of Germany.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>    \n\n===Party worker===\nHe worked till 1950 for the council in the [[Malchin]] district, some 75 km (40 miles) south-east of [[Rostock]], then from 1951 till 1952 for the regional [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] leadership at [[Mecklenburg]].  In 1952 he was appointed First secretary of the party district leadership at [[Ribnitz-Damgarten]] on the north coast.   Then, in December 1952, he was relieved of his functions \"on account of gross breach of party rules\".<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/><ref>''\"wegen grober Verletzung des Parteistatuts\"''</ref>\n\nNevertheless, between 1953 and 1958 he was second and then first secretary to the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] district leadership at [[Greifswald]], then till 1960 he was secretary for [[Agitprop|Agitation and Propaganda]] for the party district leadership in the [[Rostock]] region in succession to [[:de:Karl Zylla|Karl Zylla]]<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/> before, in 1973, moving to the other end of the country and taking a position as First Secretary of the [[Dresden]] district leadership, where his predecessor had been [[:de:Fritz Reuter (Politiker)|Fritz Reuter]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n===National politics===\nIn 1963 Krolikowski became a member of the Party Central Committee, and in 1970 he became a member of the national [[People's Chamber|People's Chamber ''(\"Volkskammer\")'']],<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/> where his responsibilities included membership of the assembly's National Defence Committee.   In 1971 he joined the party politburo's central committee.   Between 1973 and 1976 he was Secretary of the Party's Central Committee, and from 1976 right up till 1989 he was a member of the Economics Commission and of Central Committee Working Groups on the Balance of Payments and on inter-German Economic Relations.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>   From 1976 till 1988 he was First Deputy Chairman of the [[German Democratic Republic]]'s [[Council of Ministers of the GDR|Ministerial Council]].   In 1988, following the sudden death of [[:de:Werner Felfe|Werner Felfe]] (who had suffered the misfortune to be identified in western media as a possible successor to [[Erich Honecker|First Secretary Erich Honecker)]] Krolikowski regained the Central Committee secretaryship for agriculture.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n===Various reverses===\nIn November 1989 [[Die Wende|The Wall came down.]]  In November 1989 Werner Krolikowski resigned from his various public offices and on 3 December 1989 he was expelled from what had till very recently been the unchallenged [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|ruling party]] in [[East Germany]].   An investigation was launched, based on \"suspicions of abuse of office and corruption\" (''\"Verdachts auf Amtsmi\u00dfbrauch u. Korruption\"'').   In May 1990 he was charged with \"misappropriation of state funds\" (''\"Veruntreuung von Staatsgeldern\"'') and arrested before being released on bail.   However, the case was dropped on health grounds.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n==The ambassador's insight==\nThe extent to which [[East Germany]]'s leader [[Erich Honecker]] and his inner circle felt unsettled and undermined by on-going [[Perestroika]] in the [[Soviet Union]] became more widely known after Honecker himself had retired.   The Soviet ambassador in [[East Berlin]] from 1983 till 1990 was a man called [[Vyacheslav Kochemasov]], a diplomat whose experience of politics in [[Moscow]] and in [[East Berlin]] went back a long way.   He gave an interview to the western press in 1992 in which he disclosed that as far back as 1986 Werner Krolikowski had told him, in confidence, that the situation in the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] Politburo had become \"unbearable\":  policy decisions were totally driven by dogma, there was no longer any discussion, there was an absurd level of centralisation and an utterly implausible communications strategy.  Something must be done:  the leader must be replaced.<ref name=spiegel471992> {{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13681231.html |author1=Publisher-editor [[Rudolf Augstein]]|author2=|title=Schmeichelei und Unterw\u00fcrfigkeit  SPIEGEL-Interview mit Moskaus Ex-Botschafter in der DDR, Wjatscheslaw Kotschemassow, \u00fcber Erich Honecker|publisher= [[Der Spiegel]] (online)|date=16 November 1992|accessdate= 26 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Werner's brother==\nWerner Krolikowski's elder brother, [[Herbert Krolikowski]] (1924-2012) was also an East German politician of eminence.   Herbert never rose quite as far as Werner, but he did serve as East Germany's deputy foreign minister between 1963 and 1967 and again between 1975 and 1990.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenHK>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1917|author1=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]|author2=[[:de:Andreas Herbst (Historiker)|Andreas Herbst]]|title=Krolikowski, Herbert  * 15.3.1924, \u2020 28.11.2012  Stellv. Minister f\u00fcr Ausw\u00e4rtige Angelegenheiten|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1964 [[Patriotic Order of Merit]]\n* 1970 Patriotic Order of Merit\n* 1978 [[Order of Karl Marx]]\n* 1980 Patriotic Order of Merit\n\nAfter 1966 the \"[[Patriotic Order of Merit]]\", which Krolikowski received \" ([[:de:F\u00fcr Verdienste um Volk und Vaterland|\"for services to the people and the fatherland\" (''\"F\u00fcr Verdienste um Volk und Vaterland\"'')]] was awarded at three different levels, designated respectively bronze, silver and gold, so that particularly long standing providers of exceptional service not infrequently won it more than once.\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Zu einigen Fragen der F\u00fchrungst\u00e4tigkeit der Kreisleitungen der SED'', Berlin 1972\n* ''Der Kampf um die Verwirklichung der vom VIII. Parteitag beschlossenen Hauptaufgabe und die Bedeutung des wissenschaftlich-technischen Fortschritts'', Berlin 1974\n* ''Zu einigen Grundfragen der Wirtschaftspolitik der Sozialistischen Einheitspartei Deutschlands unter dem besonderen Blickpunkt der 13. Tagung des ZK der SED'', Berlin 1975\n* ''F\u00fcr wachsende und wirksamere Solidarit\u00e4tsleistungen'', Berlin 1976\n* ''Der IX. Parteitag der SED \u00fcber die Fortsetzung des politischen Kurses der Hauptaufgabe. Die Einheit von Wirtschafts- und Sozialpolitik'', Berlin 1976\n* ''Die Intensivierung der gesellschaftlichen Produktion. Hauptweg der wirtschaftlichen Entwicklung der DDR'', Leipzig 1977\n* ''Die Verantwortung der sozialistischen Staatsmacht bei der Verwirklichung der Wirtschaftsstrategie des X. Parteitages der SED'', Potsdam 1983\n* ''DDR. Bollwerk des Sozialismus und Hort des Friedens'', Potsdam 1984\n* ''Je st\u00e4rker der Sozialismus - desto sicherer der Frieden. Ausgew\u00e4hlte Reden und Aufs\u00e4tze.'', Berlin 1988\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krolikowski, Werner}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ole\u015bnica]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Lower Silesia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Politburo of the Central Committee of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of East Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the State Council of the German Democratic Republic]]\n[[Category:Members of the 4th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Volkskammer]]\n[[Category:Free German Youth members]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Karl Marx]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Patriotic Order of Merit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|honorific-prefix    = \n|birth_name    = \n|name = Werner Krolikowski\n|image = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1983-0506-026, Werner Krolikowski.jpg\n|caption = Werner Krolikowski (1985)\n|imagesize     = \n|order = \n|term_start = \n|term_end = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1928|3|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Ole\u015bnica|Oels]], [[Province of Lower Silesia]], [[Weimar Germany|Germany]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|occupation   = Politician\n|party   =   [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]]\n|spouse        =  \n|parents =    \n|children =  \n}}\n'''Werner Krolikowski''' (born 12 March 1928 <ref>[https://www.chronikderwende.de/lexikon/biografien/biographie_jsp/key=krolikowski_werner.html Chronik der Wende: Werner Krolikowski]</ref>) was an [[East Germany|East German]] political official who became a senior politician. He was a member of the Central Committee of the ruling [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED (party)]] politburo and a deputy chairman of the national [[Council of Ministers of the GDR|Council of Ministers]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1918|author1=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]|author2=[[:de:Andreas Herbst (Historiker)|Andreas Herbst]]|title=Krolikowski, Werner * 12.3.1928 Mitglied des Politb\u00fcros des ZK der SED, 1. Stellv. des Vorsitzenden des Ministerrats|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref> He also produced a number of political publications.\n\n==Life==\n===Early years===\nWerner Krolikowski was born into a working-class family.   He trained for office work.   By the time the [[Second world war|war]] ended the frontier between Poland and Germany had [[Oder-Neisse line|moved west]] and Krolikowski, along with millions of other Germans, [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|had also moved]], the town of his birth now being part of Poland.  In 1946 he joined the newly formed [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED / ''Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands'')]] in the [[Soviet occupation zone]] of what was left of Germany.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>    \n\n===Party worker===\nHe worked till 1950 for the council in the [[Malchin]] district, some 75 km (40 miles) south-east of [[Rostock]], then from 1951 till 1952 for the regional [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] leadership at [[Mecklenburg]].  In 1952 he was appointed First secretary of the party district leadership at [[Ribnitz-Damgarten]] on the north coast.   Then, in December 1952, he was relieved of his functions \"on account of gross breach of party rules\".<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/><ref>''\"wegen grober Verletzung des Parteistatuts\"''</ref>\n\nNevertheless, between 1953 and 1958 he was second and then first secretary to the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] district leadership at [[Greifswald]], then till 1960 he was secretary for [[Agitprop|Agitation and Propaganda]] for the party district leadership in the [[Rostock]] region in succession to [[:de:Karl Zylla|Karl Zylla]]<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/> before, in 1973, moving to the other end of the country and taking a position as First Secretary of the [[Dresden]] district leadership, where his predecessor had been [[:de:Fritz Reuter (Politiker)|Fritz Reuter]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n===National politics===\nIn 1963 Krolikowski became a member of the Party Central Committee, and in 1970 he became a member of the national [[People's Chamber|People's Chamber ''(\"Volkskammer\")'']],<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/> where his responsibilities included membership of the assembly's National Defence Committee.   In 1971 he joined the party politburo's central committee.   Between 1973 and 1976 he was Secretary of the Party's Central Committee, and from 1976 right up till 1989 he was a member of the Economics Commission and of Central Committee Working Groups on the Balance of Payments and on inter-German Economic Relations.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>   From 1976 till 1988 he was First Deputy Chairman of the [[German Democratic Republic]]'s [[Council of Ministers of the GDR|Ministerial Council]].   In 1988, following the sudden death of [[:de:Werner Felfe|Werner Felfe]] (who had suffered the misfortune to be identified in western media as a possible successor to [[Erich Honecker|First Secretary Erich Honecker)]] Krolikowski regained the Central Committee secretaryship for agriculture.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n===Various reverses===\nIn November 1989 [[Die Wende|The Wall came down.]]  In November 1989 Werner Krolikowski resigned from his various public offices and on 3 December 1989 he was expelled from what had till very recently been the unchallenged [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|ruling party]] in [[East Germany]].   An investigation was launched, based on \"suspicions of abuse of office and corruption\" (''\"Verdachts auf Amtsmi\u00dfbrauch u. Korruption\"'').   In May 1990 he was charged with \"misappropriation of state funds\" (''\"Veruntreuung von Staatsgeldern\"'') and arrested before being released on bail.   However, the case was dropped on health grounds.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWK/>\n\n==The ambassador's insight==\nThe extent to which [[East Germany]]'s leader [[Erich Honecker]] and his inner circle felt unsettled and undermined by on-going [[Perestroika]] in the [[Soviet Union]] became more widely known after Honecker himself had retired.   The Soviet ambassador in [[East Berlin]] from 1983 till 1990 was a man called [[Vyacheslav Kochemasov]], a diplomat whose experience of politics in [[Moscow]] and in [[East Berlin]] went back a long way.   He gave an interview to the western press in 1992 in which he disclosed that as far back as 1986 Werner Krolikowski had told him, in confidence, that the situation in the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] Politburo had become \"unbearable\":  policy decisions were totally driven by dogma, there was no longer any discussion, there was an absurd level of centralisation and an utterly implausible communications strategy.  Something must be done:  the leader must be replaced.<ref name=spiegel471992> {{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13681231.html |author1=Publisher-editor [[Rudolf Augstein]]|author2=|title=Schmeichelei und Unterw\u00fcrfigkeit  SPIEGEL-Interview mit Moskaus Ex-Botschafter in der DDR, Wjatscheslaw Kotschemassow, \u00fcber Erich Honecker|publisher= [[Der Spiegel]] (online)|date=16 November 1992|accessdate= 26 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Werner's brother==\nWerner Krolikowski's elder brother, [[Herbert Krolikowski]] (1924-2012) was also an East German politician of eminence.   Herbert never rose quite as far as Werner, but he did serve as East Germany's deputy foreign minister between 1963 and 1967 and again between 1975 and 1990.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenHK>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1917|author1=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]|author2=[[:de:Andreas Herbst (Historiker)|Andreas Herbst]]|title=Krolikowski, Herbert  * 15.3.1924, \u2020 28.11.2012  Stellv. Minister f\u00fcr Ausw\u00e4rtige Angelegenheiten|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1964 [[Patriotic Order of Merit]]\n* 1970 Patriotic Order of Merit\n* 1978 [[Order of Karl Marx]]\n* 1980 Patriotic Order of Merit\n\nAfter 1966 the \"[[Patriotic Order of Merit]]\", which Krolikowski received \" ([[:de:F\u00fcr Verdienste um Volk und Vaterland|\"for services to the people and the fatherland\" (''\"F\u00fcr Verdienste um Volk und Vaterland\"'')]] was awarded at three different levels, designated respectively bronze, silver and gold, so that particularly long standing providers of exceptional service not infrequently won it more than once.\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Zu einigen Fragen der F\u00fchrungst\u00e4tigkeit der Kreisleitungen der SED'', Berlin 1972\n* ''Der Kampf um die Verwirklichung der vom VIII. Parteitag beschlossenen Hauptaufgabe und die Bedeutung des wissenschaftlich-technischen Fortschritts'', Berlin 1974\n* ''Zu einigen Grundfragen der Wirtschaftspolitik der Sozialistischen Einheitspartei Deutschlands unter dem besonderen Blickpunkt der 13. Tagung des ZK der SED'', Berlin 1975\n* ''F\u00fcr wachsende und wirksamere Solidarit\u00e4tsleistungen'', Berlin 1976\n* ''Der IX. Parteitag der SED \u00fcber die Fortsetzung des politischen Kurses der Hauptaufgabe. Die Einheit von Wirtschafts- und Sozialpolitik'', Berlin 1976\n* ''Die Intensivierung der gesellschaftlichen Produktion. Hauptweg der wirtschaftlichen Entwicklung der DDR'', Leipzig 1977\n* ''Die Verantwortung der sozialistischen Staatsmacht bei der Verwirklichung der Wirtschaftsstrategie des X. Parteitages der SED'', Potsdam 1983\n* ''DDR. Bollwerk des Sozialismus und Hort des Friedens'', Potsdam 1984\n* ''Je st\u00e4rker der Sozialismus - desto sicherer der Frieden. Ausgew\u00e4hlte Reden und Aufs\u00e4tze.'', Berlin 1988\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krolikowski, Werner}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ole\u015bnica]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Lower Silesia]]\n[[Category:Members of the P